^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now let's discuss the 2N bid. A few weeks ago I discussed a method for distinguishing between 3 card and 4 card limit raises in competition and, in fact, that is an important distinction. |
PG| ***** 129 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|A 9-card fit is often worth an extra trick vs an 8-card fit. Most people play a cue bid in competition shows a 3 card or 4 card limit. For example, 1H-1S-2S shows a limit raise, but only promises 3 card support. It would be nice if you could distinguish between a 3 card and 4 card raise. So some people play there are 2 ways to raise in competition - a cue bid and 2N.|
PG| ***** 130 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The cheaper bid shows a 3 card limit raise, the higher bid a 4 card limit raise. For example, the auction 1H-1S-2N shows a 4 card limit raise, 1H-1S-2S a 3 card limit raise. On the other hand, the auction 1H-2C-2N shows a 3 card raise, 1H-2C-3C a 4 card raise.|
PG| ***** 131 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On this hand Eddy is stuck because 3S is a game force. So although it turns out he has a 3 card raise and the 3S is the expected bid, I would say, if you play 2N is a limit raise, in this auction 2N should show a limit raise in general, with 3 or 4 cards. I am saying the cue bid of 3S is not available to Eddy because that would force us to 4H. The raise is not a game force, only invitational.|
PG| ***** 132 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One more time let me explain the convention as it normally works. If you play this 2NT convention , you have 2 ways of showing a limit raise. One way is to cue bid the opponent's suit. The other is to bid 2NT. The cheaper of those bids shows a 3-card limit raise, the more expensive bid shows a 4-card limit raise. So, if the auction goes 1H-1S-?, 2S = 3-card limit raise, 2N = 4-card limit raise. If the auction goes 1H-2C-?, 2N = 3-card limit raise, 3C = 4-card limit raise. The purpose, of course, is to differentiate between a 3-card and 4-card limit raise, which is important for those of us who like the law of total tricks. If you do not play this, most people play that a cue bid in competition is a limit raise, but can be done with either 3-card or 4-card support. |
